node.text:
The monomyth, or hero’s journey, is a classic storytelling arc: A person is called to action and challenged by adventure, ultimately emerging transformed. @iniarchibong, the Nigerian-American artist and designer, is on a hero’s journey of his own these days, as he presents a constellation of new projects, pieces, and collections around the world. Each one is an exercise in place-making, carving out space for a Black aesthetic universe that has previously been underexplored by the mainstream.

Get acquainted with his work at our bio link. Photo by @uzooleh; words by @evaninwonderland.

When @colordept founder Julie Sariñana (@sincerelyjules) needed to give her backyard a makeover, she called designer Erick Garcia (@erickmeetsworld) of @maison_trouvaille to work his magic. Introducing our brand new YouTube series, Replace this Space!

Watch the first episode — and our other design videos — at our bio link.

node.text:
For fashion designer and lifestyle guru @jennikayne, the limited palette of interior materials—including Dinesen oak, textured plaster, and French limestone—offers relief from the unavoidable visual stimulation of her work. “I am constantly surrounded by color and texture, so when I walk into this quiet, neutral home, it feels like a blank slate. I can start to see and think clearly again,” she insists.

Explore their entire home from our September issue at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; architecture by @vincentvanduysen and @humbertonobrega; design by @jennikayne and @mollyisakseninteriors; words by @mayer.rus.

node.text:
At the recommendation of their real-estate agent and friends, Instagram's own @evachen212 and husband @tbannister enlisted the Connecticut-based design firm @hendrickschurchill to update the home. “I introduced myself over DM, my primary form of communication,” Chen jokes. “Heide [Hendricks] and Rafe [Churchill] really understood how to unlock the potential of the house, to make it warm and elegant and not too precious.”

Step into their home from our latest issue at our bio link. Photo by @chrismottalini; produced by @janekeltnerdev; styled by @kellemiles; design by @hendrickschurchill; words by @samuelcochran.

node.text:
When #AD100 architect and interior designer @charles_zana was tasked with fashioning a London apartment for a family of three, he didn’t exactly have carte blanche. After all, his clients wanted a place to showcase their striking assemblage of American art and sculptural works. Zana opted to redesign the home in an American Shaker style, emphasizing form, proportion, and functionality. 

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @matthieusalvaing; design by @charles_zana; words by @sopherring.

node.text:
A short drive from Reni Folawiyo's luxury concept store @alaralagos, in Lagos’s tony Ikoyi enclave, is another of her spectacular creations: her family home. Nestled on a quiet side street, far away from the din of honking horns and boisterous street vendors hawking everything from charred plantains to terra-cotta planters, Folawiyo’s sprawling penthouse duplex perches atop an 11-unit boutique apartment complex she and her husband, Tunde, erected. Folawiyo, who calls herself an “unapologetic proponent of the brilliance of Africa and its contemporary language,” chose award-winning Cape Town–based architecture firm @_saota for this undertaking.

Explore her exquisite home at our bio link. Photo by @iamdanielobasi; design by @__okha; architecture by @_saota; words by @lolaogunnaike.

node.text:
For model @jesshart's L.A. home, designer Carlos Mota (@casamotachic) devised a combination of patterned wall coverings and graphic stripes to replace the home’s white walls. “I love stripes, and I’ve always loved them on ceilings,” he declares, a nod to Gio Ponti homes of the 1950s. Even the floors of the living and dining rooms got the punched-up treatment with a painted-on diamond pattern overlaid with Mauritanian flat-weave rugs. (Javier Sánchez created the house’s vibrant, painted effects.) 

Explore the entire home at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @casamotachic; words by @carly_olson.

node.text:
For architect @vincentvanduysen, working on @jennikayne's L.A. home afforded a welcome opportunity to explore the intersection of his own highly distilled, Belgian-born architectural language with the lingua franca of an entirely different culture and climate. “I’m a modernist, heart and soul, and I’ve always been inspired by the particular kind of modernism that emerged in California. I was interested to see how I could participate in that history and still remain true to my own work,” the architect explains, characterizing Kayne’s home as a “beautiful synchronization of a midcentury attitude revisited by a Belgian attitude.”

Tour more of the home at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; architecture by @vincentvanduysen and @humbertonobrega; design by @jennikaynehome; words by @mayer.rus.

node.text:
Even totally empty and, by all accounts, a bit of a mess, the Paris apartment of fashion designer @pierrehardy and husband @christopherturnier was bursting with life—elaborate mythological frescoes covered almost every inch of its soaring, nearly 15-foot ceilings. Apollo, robed in crimson, harp in hand, looked down upon the entrance hall. In the living room, Juno, wife of Jupiter, and Aeolus, Greek god of wind, lounged in the clouds, while Aurora, Roman goddess of dawn—resplendent amid a magnificent medley of cherubs and horses—presided over another room. The masterworks, attributed to the artist Bon Boullogne, best known for his easel paintings found at Versailles and the Louvre, were a serious selling point.

Explore their elegant apartment at our bio link. Photo by @francoishalard; design by @vdecotiis; words by @_h_mart_.

node.text:
Maximizing natural light and modernizing the once octagonal floor plan were just two of the goals designer @arielokin had when it came to the renovation of an apartment on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan. Hired by a couple who wished to preserve the bones of the beautiful pre-war-era home overlooking Central Park, Ariel aimed to maintain as much original detailing, like the beveled glass pocket doors, while reimagining the layout, adding sleek fixtures, plus an array of art and midcentury furnishings. The result? A layered, serene space with pops of bold color.

Go behind the design – and read more from @getclever – at our bio link. Photo by @donnadotanphoto; design by @arielokin; words by Lauren Jones.

node.text:
In this mountainside home in Big Sky, Montana, designer Roger Higgins (@rhigginsinteriors) used Venetian plaster and wall coverings to imbue the home with more warmth than paint alone could provide. A @kravetinc fabric seen in the boys’ bedroom, and textured wallpapers, such as one @phillipjeffriesltd selection, proved to be particularly exemplary selections.

Tour the entire home at our bio link. Photo by @haris.kenjar; design by @rhigginsinteriors; words by @ericrallen.

node.text:
“Instead of drywall and paint, we try to use natural materials and finishes to establish the color palette and the mood,” notes @woods_dangaran partner Joseph Dangaran, emphasizing the warmth of this L.A. home's composition. Natural illumination from a skylight animates the primary bath. The architects honed the Patagonia marble to minimize the stone’s reflectivity.

Tour the beautiful spaces at our bio link. Photo by @joefletcherphoto; design by @woods_dangaran; words by @mayer.rus.
